         <abstract>
            <p>The accurate prediction of rotor thrust is important in order to analyze the strength of the rotor blades and supporting tower of the horizontal-axis wind turbines. In the present work, a series of model wind turbines were tested in a wind tunnel to ascertain the thrust of the rotor. The effect of three design parameters on the thrust - the number of the blades, the pitch angle, and the up-tilt angle of the rotor plane — were tested for several wind speeds. The experiments show that, keeping two of the three design parameters unchanged, the thrust on the rotor descreases with increasing pitch angle and up-tilt angle, and increases with increasing number of blades.The test results correlate well with the theoretical values. Moreover, the relationship between the thrust coefficient and the torque coefficient was also clarified.</p>
         </abstract>
